03971nam a22006375i 9780292769779DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211985txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927697797 a10.7560/7508762doi  a(DE-B1597)587654  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHB915b.B4 1985 7aSOC0260102bisacsh04a304.6/32/08968720732191 aBean, Frank D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMexican American Fertility Patterns /cGray Swicegood, Frank D. Bean. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1985  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Racial and Ethnic Fertility Research: From Description to Theory -- t3. The Idea of Opportunity Costs and Minority/Majority Fertility Differences -- t4. Sources of Data and Methodological Considerations -- t5. Generational Status and Fertility -- t6. Language Patterns, Female Education and Employment, and Fertility -- t7. Juxtaposition of Opportunity Costs and Minority Group Status Hypotheses -- t8. Summary and Conclusions -- tAppendices -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mexican American population is the fastest growing major racial/ethnic group in the United States. During the decade 1970–1980, the Mexican origin population increased from 4.5 million to 8.7 million persons. High fertility, not immigration, was responsible for nearly two-thirds of this growth. Recent and historical evidence shows that women of Mexican origin or descent bear significantly more children than other white women in the United States. Mexican American Fertility Patterns clarifies the nature and magnitude of these fertility differences by analyzing patterns of childbearing both across ethnic groups and within the Mexican American population. Using data from the 1970 and 1980 U.S. Censuses and from the 1976 Survey of Income and Education, the authors evaluate various hypotheses of cultural, social, demographic, and/or economic factors as determinants of fertility differences. Empirical analyses center on the interrelationships between fertility and generational status, language usage and proficiency, and female education. This timely report concludes that Mexican American fertility is closest to that of other whites under conditions of greater access to the opportunity structures of the society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFertility, HumanzUnited States. 0aFertility, Human--United States. 0aMexican AmericansxPopulation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aSwicegood, Gray, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769779423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769779/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK